### Description

I am working with HTTP streaming APIs following the [raw events](https://angular.dev/guide/http/making-requests#receiving-raw-progress-events) pattern.

When I use an `if` statement to narrow down the `HttpEventType` to `DownloadProgress`, the TS compiler doesn't get access to the `partialText` property unless I cast it using `event as HttpDownloadProgressEvent`.

**Example**
```typescript
this.http.post(
  '/foobar',
  { foo: 'bar' },
  { observe: 'events', reportProgress: true }
).pipe(
  map((event) => {
    if (event.type === HttpEventType.DownloadProgress) {
      // This fails to compile with "Property 'partialText' does not exist on type 'HttpProgressEvent'."
      console.log('incremental text', event.partialText);
      // This works
      console.log(
        'incremental text',
        (event as HttpDownloadProgressEvent).partialText
      );
    }
  })
);
```

My expectation is that the TS compiler gets knowledge of the `partialText` property once the event type is determined to be download progress.


